ic is line-resilient** — `release.yml` uses pattern-based `awk` (lines 323-327, 343-347) to replace `__REPO_PLACEHOLDER__` / `__VERSION_PLACEHOLDER__` / `__CHECKSUMS_PLACEHOLDER__`, and `${{ github.repository }}` populates `REPO`. Works on the fork unchanged.\n\n---\n\n## Design (chosen approach)\n\n| Concern | Choice |\n|---|---|\n| Binary host | GitHub Releases on `Faker-r/git-ai` |\n| Install script host | GitHub release asset on `Faker-r/git-ai` (no Railway hop) |\n| Server in CI run | Not touched at all |\n| Build matrix | Full (6 targets: linux x64/arm64, macOS x64/arm64, windows x64/arm64) |\n\n**Why direct to GitHub instead of via Railway:** every release publishes a fully-templated `install.sh` as a release asset (with `REPO`, `PINNED_VERSION`, and `EMBEDDED_CHECKSUMS` baked in by `release.yml:323-327`). The workflow can curl that asset directly. The Railway server only earns its keep if/when the binary actually hits `API_BASE` for CAS/metrics/auth — which the CI path never does. Skipping the redirect means: no env var, no redeploy, one fewer service that can fail the CI run.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation steps\n\n### 1. Sanity-check the fork's release pipeline\n\nFiles to know about (no edits required for the matrix build itself):\n- `.github/workflows/release.yml` — matrix build + release publishing. Templating at lines 320-327 (install.sh) and 340-347 (install.ps1). Asset attach at lines 414-418.\n- `.github/workflows/build-macos-intel.yml` — separate x86_64-apple-darwin job invoked by release.yml.\n- `install.sh` — placeholders intact at lines 53, 60, 65; URL construction at lines 265/269/273.\n\n**Recommended one edit:** Guard or delete the `next-element-inc/monorepo` trigger at `release.yml:477-488` so the run finishes green on the fork. Either:\n- Wrap in `if: ${{ github.repository == 'git-ai-project/git-ai' }}`, or\n- Delete the step. (Recommended — it's not relevant to your fork.)\n\n**Optional cleanup** (not required):\n- Delete `release-intellij-plugin.yml` and `release-vscode-extension.yml`. You don't need plugin releases for CI.\n- Leave `install-scripts-local.yml` / `install-scripts-nightly.yml` — useful as smoke tests.\n\n**Cut the first release:**\n1. Push the fork to `Faker-r/git-ai` if not already.\n2. Open Actions → \"Release\" → Run workflow with `dry_run=false`, `release_production=true`, version `v0.0.1` (or whatever you pick).\n3. Confirm the resulting release page has all 6 binaries + `install.sh` + `install.ps1` + `SHA256SUMS`.\n4. Verify the published `install.sh` by downloading it and grepping: `REPO=\"Faker-r/git-ai\"`, `PINNED_VERSION=\"v0.0.1\"`, and a non-placeholder `EMBEDDED_CHECKSUMS=`.\n\n### 2. Update the CI workflow on `git-ai-testing`\n\n**File to modify:** `git-ai-testing/.github/workflows/git-ai.yaml`\n\nChange one line (the curl URL) to point straight at the fork's latest release asset:\n\n```yaml\n- name: Install git-ai\n  run: |\n    curl -fsSL https://github.com/Faker-r/git-ai/releases/latest/download/install.sh | bash\n    echo \"$HOME/.git-ai/bin\" >> $GITHUB_PATH\n```\n\nEverything else stays the same. The existing `permissions: contents: write` is correct — it's what lets `git-ai` push the rewritten authorship notes back to `origin`.\n\n**No Railway changes required.** `self-hosted-server/main.py` is untouched. The Railway server stays as it is for any future use (CAS/metrics/auth), but is not on the CI critical path.\n\n---\n\n## What you might be missing (worth flagging)\n\n1. **First release must exist before CI works.** The `releases/latest/download/install.sh` URL 404s until you've published at least one tagged release on `Faker-r/git-ai`. Don't merge a PR in `git-ai-testing` until step 1 is done.\n2. **`git-ai install-hooks` runs during install.sh** — wires IDE hooks. In a clean CI runner this should silently no-op or warn; install.sh wraps it in `if !` so it can't fail the install. Watch the first run's logs anyway.\n3. **The `next-element-inc/monorepo` step on release.yml:477-488** will fail without `RELEASE_CHANNEL_TOKEN`. Guard or remove it (covered above).\n4. **`GITHUB_TOKEN` push permission for notes refs.** The workflow already grants `contents: write`. If `main` on `git-ai-testing` is ever protected with required-status-checks that block bot pushes, the notes push will fail — you'd need a PAT or actions exemption.\n5. **No need for `INSTALL_NONCE` / `API_BASE` plumbing.** Since CI run doesn't touch the server, leave them unset. The binary's `exchange-nonce` step is skipped when `INSTALL_NONCE` is empty (`install.sh:339`).\n6. **Apple Silicon / Windows runner labels.** `release.yml` matrix uses `ubuntu-22.04-arm`, `macos-latest`, `windows-latest`, etc. — all are valid GitHub-hosted labels at time of writing. If a build fails with \"no matching runner\", check label availability for your account.\n\n---\n\n## Critical files\n\n- `git-ai/.github/workflows/release.yml` — already correct for fork; one recommended edit at lines 477-488 (guard or delete the `next-element-inc/monorepo` step so the run goes green on the fork)\n- `git-ai/install.sh` — no edits\n- `git-ai/self-hosted-server/*` — **not touched**\n- `git-ai-testing/.github/workflows/git-ai.yaml` — change curl URL to `https://github.com/Faker-r/git-ai/releases/latest/download/install.sh`\n\n## Verification (end-to-end)\n\n1. **Release cuts cleanly.** Manually dispatch `release.yml` on `Faker-r/git-ai` → confirm release page shows all 6 binaries + `install.sh` + `install.ps1` + `SHA256SUMS`. Download the release's `install.sh` and grep: `REPO=\"Faker-r/git-ai\"`, `PINNED_VERSION=\"v0.0.1\"`, `EMBEDDED_CHECKSUMS=` is non-empty.\n2. **Install script works on a Linux box.** `curl -fsSL https://github.com/Faker-r/git-ai/releases/latest/download/install.sh | bash` → confirm `~/.git-ai/bin/git-ai --version` matches the release tag and that the install logged `Checksum verified for git-ai-linux-x64`.\n3. **CI run end-to-end.** In `git-ai-testing`, open a PR, merge it, watch