            "content": "# git-ai Release & CI Pipeline: How It Works\n\n## Context\n\ngit-ai is distributed as prebuilt binaries downloaded by an install script. The install script (`install.sh`) is itself templated at release time so each release pins itself to specific binaries with verified checksums. The CI integration (`git-ai ci github run`) is invoked from a GitHub Actions workflow on merged PRs and rewrites authorship notes via git refs — without contacting any application server.\n\nThis document captures the full pipeline as it currently exists in the fork at `Faker-r/git-ai`, and how the pieces connect end-to-end. It exists so future work on releases, install distribution, or CI doesn't have to re-trace the same code.\n\n---\n\n## 1. The release workflow\n\n**File:** `git-ai/.github/workflows/release.yml`\n\n### 1.1 Trigger\n\n`workflow_dispatch` only (lines 8-20). There is no tag-push or schedule trigger. A release is cut by manually running the workflow from the GitHub Actions UI with these inputs:\n\n- `dry_run` (default `true`) — must be set to `false` to actually publish.\n- `release_production` (default `false`) — set `true` to also bump the version in `Cargo.toml` and push the tag.\n- `version` — the release tag (e.g. `v0.0.1`).\n\n### 1.2 Build matrix\n\nSix target binaries are produced, across two jobs:\n\n**`build` matrix job** (5 targets):\n| Target | Runner | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| `x86_64-unknown-linux-musl` | `ubuntu-22.04` | Built inside Docker; statically linked musl, no glibc dependency |\n| `aarch64-unknown-linux-musl` | `ubuntu-22.04-arm` | Built inside Docker; statically linked musl |\n| `x86_64-pc-windows-msvc` | `windows-latest` | MSVC toolchain |\n| `aarch64-pc-windows-msvc` | `windows-latest` | Cross-compiled MSVC |\n| `aarch64-apple-darwin` | `macos-latest` | Apple Silicon |\n\n**`build-macos-intel` job** (separate, see `.github/workflows/build-macos-intel.yml`):\n| Target | Runner |\n|---|---|\n| `x86_64-apple-darwin` | `macos-13` |\n\nEach binary is built with `cargo build --release --target <TARGET>`, stripped, verified for the correct architecture, and uploaded as a workflow artifact.\n\n### 1.3 Install script templating\n\nThis is the central piece of the pipeline. The source `install.sh` ships with three placeholder strings:\n\n```bash\nREPO=\"__REPO_PLACEHOLDER__\"                       # install.sh line 53\nPINNED_VERSION=\"__VERSION_PLACEHOLDER__\"          # install.sh line 60\nEMBEDDED_CHECKSUMS=\"__CHECKSUMS_PLACEHOLDER__\"    # install.sh line 65\n```\n\nAt release time, `release.yml` (lines 320-327) runs an `awk` substitution that pattern-matches on the variable names (not line numbers, so it survives source edits) and replaces:\n\n- `__REPO_PLACEHOLDER__` → `${{ github.repository }}` (e.g. `Faker-r/git-ai`)\n- `__VERSION_PLACEHOLDER__` → the input version (e.g. `v0.0.1`)\n- `__CHECKSUMS_PLACEHOLDER__` → pipe-separated `sha256sum  filename` entries for every binary asset\n\nA parallel block (lines 340-347) does the same for `install.ps1`. Both templated scripts are then attached to the GitHub release as assets (lines 414-418), alongside the six binaries, `SHA256SUMS`, and build attestations (`actions/attest-build-provenance`, line 357).\n\n### 1.4 Fork-blocking step\n\nLines 477-488 invoke a workflow in `next-element-inc/monorepo` using `RELEASE_CHANNEL_TOKEN`. This secret does not exist on a fork (`Faker-r/git-ai`) and the step will fail. It runs *after* binary build and release publish, so artifacts are still produced — but the run goes red. To get a green run on the fork, guard with `if: ${{ github.repository == 'git-ai-project/git-ai' }}` or delete the step.\n\n### 1.5 Release page contents (post-run)\n\nA successful run produces a release at `https://github.com/Faker-r/git-ai/releases/<tag>` with:\n\n- `git-ai-macos-x64`, `git-ai-macos-arm64`\n- `git-ai-linux-x64`, `git-ai-linux-arm64`\n- `git-ai-windows-x64.exe`, `git-ai-windows-arm64.exe`\n- `install.sh` (templated for this release)\n- `install.ps1` (templated for this release)\n- `SHA256SUMS`\n\nStable URLs:\n\n- `https://github.com/<repo>/releases/<tag>/download/<asset>` — pinned to a specific tag\n- `https://github.com/<repo>/releases/latest/download/<asset>` — auto-resolves to the most recent release\n\n---\n\n## 2. The install script\n\n**File:** `git-ai/install.sh`\n\n### 2.1 What it does, step by step\n\n1. **Resolves `HOME` and `SHELL`** robustly, including under JAMF/MDM where these may be unset (lines 8-42).\n2. **Detects the standard `git` binary path** for later use as `git-og` (lines 172-218). Refuses any path containing `git-ai` to prevent recursion.\n3. **Detects OS and architecture** (lines 224-252): maps `x86_64`→`x64`, `aarch64`/`arm64`→`arm64`, `darwin`→`macos`, `linux`→`linux`. Builds `BINARY_NAME` like `git-ai-macos-arm64`.\n4. **Resolves which release to download** (lines 259-274), in priority order:\n   - `GIT_AI_LOCAL_BINARY` env var → install from a local file\n   - `PINNED_VERSION` (replaced at template time) → that exact version\n   - `GIT_AI_RELEASE_TAG` env var → that version\n   - else → `latest`\n5. **Downloads the binary** to `~/.git-ai/bin/git-ai` and verifies the SHA-256 checksum against `EMBEDDED_CHECKSUMS` (lines 82-125). On failure, the binary is removed and install aborts.\n6. **Symlinks** `~/.git-ai/bin/git` → `git-ai` (so `git` becomes git-ai), and `~/.git-ai/bin/git-og` → the standard git path (so the original git is still reachable).\n7. **Removes the macOS quarantine xattr** so the binary runs without a Gatekeeper prompt (lines 318-320).\n8. **Creates `~/.local/bin/git-ai` symlink** if `~/.local/bin` is on PATH (lines 322-328).\n9. **Optionally exchanges an install nonce** for credentials (lines 338-343): if both `INSTALL_NONCE` and `API_BASE` are set, runs `git-ai exchange-nonce`. **Both are unset in CI**, so this is a no-op.\n10. **Runs `git-ai install-hooks`** (line 346) to wire IDE/agent hooks. Wrapped in `if !` — failure does not abort install.\n11. **Writes `~/.git-ai/config.json`** with `git_path` pointing at the standard git binary and `feature_flags.async_mode: true` (lines 352-368). Only created if absent — does not overwrite existing config.\n12. **Adds `~/.git-ai/bin` to PATH** in every detected shell config (`.bashrc`, `.bash_profile`, `.zshrc`, fish config) — lines 375-406.\n13. **Falls back to interactive `git-ai login`** if the nonce exchange failed (line 463).\n\n### 2.2 What the install script depends on\n\n- `curl` with `--fail --location --silent --show-error` (line 292).\n- Either `sha256sum` or `shasum -a 256` for checksum verification. If neither is present, verification is skipped with a warning (lines 110-117).\n- A working standard `git` binary on PATH (or recoverable from `~/.git-ai/config.json`).\n\n### 2.3 Two ways to fetch the install script\n\n| Source | URL | Trade-offs |\n|---|---|---|\n| Direct GitHub release asset | `https://github.com/Faker-r/git-ai/releases/latest/download/install.sh` | Simplest. Templated for that release. Pinned by GitHub's `releases/latest` resolution. |\n| Self-hosted redirect | `https://git-ai-production.up.railway.app/install.sh` (not currently implemented) | Adds an indirection layer where you can later inject env vars (e.g. `API_BASE`) before the script runs. Currently unnecessary. |\n\nFor the CI use case, the direct GitHub URL is sufficient and removes the Railway server from the install path.\n\n---\n\n## 3. The CI command\n\n### 3.1 Entry point\n\n`git-ai ci github run` is dispatched in `git-ai/src/commands/ci_handlers.rs:52-110`. The flow:\n\n1. `get_github_ci_context()` reads the GitHub event payload (`GITHUB_EVENT_NAME`, `GITHUB_EVENT_PATH`), confirms it's a merged `pull_request`, clones the base branch with `GITHUB_TOKEN` auth, and fetches PR commits via the special `pull/<n>/head` ref. (`src/ci/github.rs:39-115`)\n2. `ci_context.run()` (`src/ci/ci_context.rs:69-254`) decides whether the PR was a squash, rebase, or merge commit, and calls one of:\n   - `rewrite_authorship_after_rebase_v2()` (`src/authorship/rebase_authorship.rs:1088+`)\n   - `rewrite_authorship_after_squash_or_rebase()` (`src/authorship/rebase_authorship.rs:563+`)\n3. Pushes the rewritten authorship notes back to `origin` via `self.repo.push_authorship(\"origin\")` (`src/ci/ci_context.rs:238`).\n4. `ci_context.teardown()` (lines 256-263) cleans up the temp clone unless `--no-cleanup` is passed.\n\n### 3.2 What it touches over the network\n\n**Only git operations.** The CI run path imports nothing from `crate::api_client` and never calls `api_base_url()`. All \"uploads\" happen as git note pushes via the `GITHUB_TOKEN`-authenticated remote.\n\nThis means:\n- No `API_BASE` is needed.\n- No `INSTALL_NONCE` / `StoredCredentials` is needed.\n- The Railway self-hosted server (or upstream `usegitai.com`) is not involved at all in CI.\n\n### 3.3 Result codes\n\n`ci_handlers.rs:7-28` translates `CiRunResult` to one of:\n- `authorship rewritten successfully`\n- `authorship already exists`\n- `skipped simple merge (authorship preserved)`\n- `skipped fast-forward merge`\n- `no AI authorship to track (pre-git-ai commits or human-only code)`\n\nAll five are exit-0 outcomes. The workflow only fails on actual errors (missing event payload, git clone failure, push rejection, etc.).\n\n### 3.4 Failure modes worth knowing\n\n- **Notes ref push rejected.** If `main` on the testing repo is protected with required-status-checks that block bot pushes, the notes push fails. Fix: grant the workflow's token push access, or use a PAT.\n- **Missing `permissions: contents: write`.** Default `GITHUB_TOKEN` is read-only on PRs from forks. The workflow at `git-ai-testing/.github/workflows/git-ai.yaml:11-12` already grants `contents: write`; don't drop it.\n- **`fetch_authorship_notes()` finds no notes.** Returns `NotesExistence::NotFound` and the run continues silently (`src/git/sync_authorship.rs:170-175`). Not an error.\n\n---\n\n## 4. The self-hosted server\n\n**Directory:** `git-ai/self-hosted-server/`\n\n### 4.1 Routes (current state)\n\n| Route | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `GET /health` | Liveness check |\n| `POST /worker/cas/upload` | Upload AI conversation transcripts (CAS) |\n| `GET /worker/cas/` | Read CAS objects by hash |\n| `POST /worker/metrics/upload` | Upload telemetry events |\n| `POST /worker/oauth/device/code` | Mint device code (CLI OAuth flow) |\n| `POST /worker/oauth/token` | Exchange device code or refresh token |\n| `GET /device` | Browser UI for OAuth flow |\n| `GET /device/callback` | OAuth redirect target |\n| `POST /device/approve` | Bind authenticated session to device code |\n\n### 4.2 Stack\n\n- **FastAPI** + **Uvicorn**.\n- **Supabase** (managed Postgres) for storage and auth (Google provider).\n- **Pydantic** for request/response models with `ExcludeNoneModel` mirroring Rust's serde behavior.\n- **JCS** (RFC 8785 JSON canonicalization) for hash verification — see `hash_utils.py`.\n\n### 4.3 Schema\n\nThree tables (`schema.sql`):\n- `cas_objects` — content-addressed JSON store, indexed by user_id and creation time.\n- `metrics_events` — telemetry, indexed by user_id, event_id (1-4), and repo_url.\n- `device_codes` — OAuth device flow state.\n\n### 4.4 Deployment\n\nThe server runs on Railway at `https://git-ai-production.up.railway.app`. **There is no deployment manifest in the repo** (no `Dockerfile`, `Procfile`, or `railway.json`). Railway is configured via its dashboard — auto-detects Python from `requirements.txt` and uses a `uvicorn main:app` start command.\n\nAdding a new route is therefore a pure Python edit followed by a git push to the connected branch; Railway redeploys automatically.\n\n### 4.5 Role in CI\n\n**None, currently.** The server's CAS/metrics/auth endpoints exist for the *interactive* git-ai use case (developer commits with `git commit` and prompts get uploaded). The CI command rewrites notes via git refs only — it does not interact with this server. If you ever wire the binary to upload CI-rewritten authorship notes to CAS for centralized inspection, that would be the point at which the server enters the CI critical path.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Putting it all together: the CI loop\n\n```\n[PR merged on git-ai-testing]\n        │\n        ▼\n[GitHub Actions workflow fires (on: pull_request, types: [closed])]\n        │\n        ▼\n[Step: curl install.sh from github.com/Faker-r/git-ai/releases/latest]\n        │   ↓ install.sh downloads git-ai-linux-x64,\n        │   ↓ verifies sha256 against EMBEDDED_CHECKSUMS,\n        │   ↓ symlinks ~/.git-ai/bin/git-ai\n        │   ↓ skips exchange-nonce (INSTALL_NONCE unset)\n        ▼\n[Step: git-ai ci github run]\n        │   ↓ reads GITHUB_EVENT_PATH\n        │   ↓ clones base branch with GITHUB_TOKEN\n        │   ↓ fetches pull/<n>/head\n        │   ↓ rewrites authorship notes locally\n        │   ↓ git push origin refs/notes/* (using GITHUB_TOKEN)\n        ▼\n[Workflow exits 0]\n```\n\nNo API server touched. No nonce exchanged. The only external dependencies on the critical path are GitHub Releases (for the binary) and the testing repo's own remote (for the notes push).\n\n---\n\n## 6. Cross-references\n\n- Plan for setting up CI on the fork: `~/.claude/plans/im-trying-to-setup-crystalline-pascal.md`\n- Earlier self-hosting design: `documentation/git_ai_self_hosting_plan.md`\n- General git-ai internals: `documentation/git_ai_understanding.md`\n- Research-branch behavioral diffs: `documentation/git-ai-research-branch-changes.md`\n",
